1
00:03:12,442 --> 00:03:14,774
Hi. I've got an appointment
with Mr. Ullman.

2
00:03:14,985 --> 00:03:16,943
My name is Jack Torrance.

3
00:03:17,114 --> 00:03:19,651
His office is the first door
on the left.

4
00:03:19,865 --> 00:03:21,105
Thank you.

5
00:03:37,134 --> 00:03:38,123
[KNOCKS]

6
00:03:38,300 --> 00:03:39,507
-Mr. Ullman?
-Yes.

7
00:03:39,677 --> 00:03:42,966
-I'm Jack Torrance.
-Oh, come on in, Jack.

8
00:03:44,057 --> 00:03:46,593
-Very nice to meet you.
-Nice to meet you.

9
00:03:46,810 --> 00:03:48,800
-This is my secretary, Susie.
-Hello.

10
00:03:48,978 --> 00:03:51,219
-Susie, how do you do?
-Any trouble finding us?

11
00:03:51,439 --> 00:03:54,272
No problem at all.
I made the trip in 3 1/2 hours.

12
00:03:54,484 --> 00:03:56,349
That's very good time.

13
00:03:56,694 --> 00:03:58,311
Sit down a minute, Jack.

14
00:03:58,530 --> 00:04:00,316
Just make yourself at home.

15
00:04:00,490 --> 00:04:01,776
Like some coffee?

16
00:04:01,991 --> 00:04:04,484
If you're having some,
I wouldn't mind. Thanks.

17
00:04:04,661 --> 00:04:05,651
-Susie.
-Sure.

18
00:04:05,871 --> 00:04:07,611
And ask Bill Watson to join us.

19
00:04:07,830 --> 00:04:09,241
Yes, I will.

20
00:04:17,966 --> 00:04:19,798
[MUSIC PLAYS ON TV]

21
00:04:20,134 --> 00:04:21,250
Mom?

22
00:04:22,137 --> 00:04:23,298
Yeah?

23
00:04:23,680 --> 00:04:27,343
Do you really want to go and live
in that hotel for the winter?

24
00:04:27,934 --> 00:04:29,298
Sure I do.

25
00:04:29,519 --> 00:04:31,430
It'll be lots of fun.

26
00:04:33,314 --> 00:04:35,396
Yeah. I guess so.

27
00:04:35,608 --> 00:04:39,773
Anyway, there's hardly anybody
to play with around here.

28
00:04:40,572 --> 00:04:44,189
I know. It always takes
a little time to make new friends.

29
00:04:45,701 --> 00:04:47,988
Yeah, I guess so.

30
00:04:48,747 --> 00:04:49,781
What about Tony?

31
00:04:49,997 --> 00:04:52,365
He's looking forward
to the hotel, I bet.

32
00:04:52,918 --> 00:04:55,284
[IN TONY'S VOICE]
<i>No, I ain't, Mrs. Torrance.</i>

33
00:04:55,711 --> 00:04:58,124
Now, come on, Tony.
Don't be silly.

34
00:04:58,548 --> 00:05:00,538
<i>I don't want to go there.</i>

35
00:05:01,009 --> 00:05:03,045
How come you don't want to go?

36
00:05:03,261 --> 00:05:05,298
<i>I just don't.</i>

37
00:05:05,805 --> 00:05:08,389
Let's just wait and see.

38
00:05:08,641 --> 00:05:11,350
We're all going to have
a real good time.

39
00:05:12,728 --> 00:05:15,187
Bill, I'd like you
to meet Jack Torrance.

40
00:05:15,398 --> 00:05:16,809
How do you do, Bill?

41
00:05:17,024 --> 00:05:18,981
-Nice to meet you.
-Pleasure to meet you.

42
00:05:19,194 --> 00:05:21,105
Grab a chair, Bill. Join in.

43
00:05:21,321 --> 00:05:25,439
Jack is going to take care of
the Overlook for us this winter.

44
00:05:25,699 --> 00:05:28,612
I'd like you to take him around
soon as we're through.

45
00:05:28,786 --> 00:05:29,776
Fine.

46
00:05:30,413 --> 00:05:31,949
Jack is a schoolteacher.

47
00:05:32,122 --> 00:05:34,581
Uh, formerly a schoolteacher.

48
00:05:34,750 --> 00:05:36,457
BILL:
What line of work are you in now?

49
00:05:36,670 --> 00:05:38,252
I'm a writer.

50
00:05:38,504 --> 00:05:42,122
Teaching's been more or less
a way of making ends meet.

51
00:05:42,341 --> 00:05:44,298
This ought to be
quite a change for you.

52
00:05:44,511 --> 00:05:47,048
Well, I'm looking for a change.

53
00:05:47,264 --> 00:05:50,848
Our people in Denver recommended
Jack very highly, and for once...

54
00:05:51,058 --> 00:05:52,641
...I agree with them.

55
00:05:53,269 --> 00:05:55,101
Let's see, where were we?

56
00:05:55,271 --> 00:05:57,889
I was about to explain...

57
00:05:58,108 --> 00:06:02,271
...that our season here runs from
May 15th to October 30th.

58
00:06:02,487 --> 00:06:05,946
Then we close down completely
until the following May.

59
00:06:06,156 --> 00:06:08,944
Do you mind if I ask why you do that?

60
00:06:09,160 --> 00:06:12,619
It seems to me that the skiing
up here would be fantastic.

61
00:06:12,831 --> 00:06:15,447
It would be. The problem is
the enormous cost...

62
00:06:15,625 --> 00:06:18,207
...it would be to keep
the road to Sidewinder open.

63
00:06:18,836 --> 00:06:20,577
It's a 25-mile stretch of road.

64
00:06:20,797 --> 00:06:23,129
It gets 20 feet of snow
during the winter.

65
00:06:23,341 --> 00:06:26,584
There's just no way to make it
economically feasible...

66
00:06:26,802 --> 00:06:28,713
...to keep it clear.

67
00:06:28,930 --> 00:06:31,297
When the place was built in 1907...

68
00:06:31,473 --> 00:06:34,057
...there was very little interest
in winter sports.

69
00:06:34,269 --> 00:06:39,139
This site was chosen for its
seclusion and scenic beauty.

70
00:06:39,356 --> 00:06:41,894
It's certainly got plenty of that.

71
00:06:42,110 --> 00:06:43,316
That's right.

72
00:06:43,987 --> 00:06:46,819
Did they give you any idea in Denver...

73
00:06:47,031 --> 00:06:48,692
...about what the job entails?

74
00:06:48,908 --> 00:06:50,990
Only in a very general way.

75
00:06:51,827 --> 00:06:53,238
Well...

76
00:06:53,663 --> 00:06:56,074
...the winters can be fantastically cruel.

77
00:06:56,290 --> 00:06:59,750
The basic idea is to cope
with the very costly damage...

78
00:06:59,961 --> 00:07:01,951
...and depreciation
which can occur.

79
00:07:02,172 --> 00:07:04,584
This consists mainly
of running the boiler...

80
00:07:04,798 --> 00:07:08,757
...heating different parts of the
hotel on a daily rotating basis...

81
00:07:08,970 --> 00:07:11,677
...repairing damage as it occurs...

82
00:07:11,848 --> 00:07:14,680
...and doing repairs so the
elements can't get a foothold.

83
00:07:15,769 --> 00:07:18,009
That sounds fine to me.

84
00:07:18,396 --> 00:07:21,353
Physically, it's not
a very demanding job.

85
00:07:21,565 --> 00:07:24,728
The only thing that can get a bit
trying here during the winter...

86
00:07:24,944 --> 00:07:27,562
...is a tremendous sense
of isolation.

87
00:07:28,697 --> 00:07:33,283
That just happens to be
exactly what I'm looking for.

88
00:07:33,620 --> 00:07:36,737
I'm outlining a new writing project.

89
00:07:37,165 --> 00:07:40,452
Five months of peace
is just what I want.

90
00:07:41,211 --> 00:07:42,951
That's very good, Jack.

91
00:07:43,254 --> 00:07:46,417
Because, for some people...

92
00:07:46,632 --> 00:07:48,374
...solitude...

93
00:07:48,593 --> 00:07:50,209
...and isolation...

94
00:07:50,387 --> 00:07:53,379
...can, of itself, become a problem.

95
00:07:54,182 --> 00:07:55,764
Not for me.

96
00:07:56,308 --> 00:07:59,552
How about your wife and son?
Do you think they'll take to it?

97
00:08:01,355 --> 00:08:02,516
They'll love it.

98
00:08:02,732 --> 00:08:03,892
Great.

99
00:08:05,401 --> 00:08:10,067
Well, before I turn you over to Bill...

100
00:08:10,240 --> 00:08:13,733
...there's one other thing I think
we should talk about.

101
00:08:13,951 --> 00:08:15,408
Not to sound melodramatic...

102
00:08:15,577 --> 00:08:18,161
...but it's been known to
give a few people...

103
00:08:18,372 --> 00:08:20,579
...second thoughts about the job.

104
00:08:21,250 --> 00:08:22,911
I'm intrigued.

105
00:08:23,127 --> 00:08:25,459
I don't suppose they
said anything in Denver...

106
00:08:25,672 --> 00:08:29,630
...about the tragedy we had up here
during the winter of 1970.

107
00:08:30,259 --> 00:08:32,250
I don't believe they did.

108
00:08:33,178 --> 00:08:34,760
ULLMAN:
Well....

109
00:08:35,181 --> 00:08:37,263
My predecessor in this job...

110
00:08:37,433 --> 00:08:40,471
...hired a man named Charles Grady
as the winter caretaker.

111
00:08:40,687 --> 00:08:44,225
He came up with his wife and
two little girls of about 8 and 10.

112
00:08:44,441 --> 00:08:47,432
He had a good employment record,
good references.

113
00:08:47,610 --> 00:08:49,897
And from what I've been told,
he seemed...

114
00:08:50,113 --> 00:08:52,774
...like a completely
normal individual.

115
00:08:52,990 --> 00:08:55,357
But at some point during the winter...

116
00:08:55,576 --> 00:08:59,195
...he must have suffered some kind
of a complete mental breakdown.

117
00:08:59,413 --> 00:09:01,780
He ran amuck...

118
00:09:05,169 --> 00:09:07,376
...and killed his family
with an ax.

119
00:09:08,630 --> 00:09:13,296
Stacked them neatly in a room
in the west wing, and then...

120
00:09:14,095 --> 00:09:17,803
...he put both barrels
of his shotgun in his mouth.

121
00:09:19,017 --> 00:09:20,802
The police thought...

122
00:09:21,019 --> 00:09:25,104
...that it was what the old-timers
used to call cabin fever.

123
00:09:25,315 --> 00:09:28,307
A kind of claustrophobic reaction
which can occur...

124
00:09:28,525 --> 00:09:32,644
...when people are shut in together
over long periods of time.

125
00:09:34,823 --> 00:09:36,313
Wow.

126
00:09:37,744 --> 00:09:39,154
That is...

127
00:09:39,370 --> 00:09:40,905
...quite a story.

128
00:09:42,206 --> 00:09:43,663
Yeah, it is.

129
00:09:44,793 --> 00:09:48,081
It's still hard for me to believe
it actually happened here.

130
00:09:48,421 --> 00:09:50,128
But it did.

131
00:09:50,340 --> 00:09:51,705
And, uh...

132
00:09:51,883 --> 00:09:55,922
...I think you can appreciate
why I wanted to tell you about it.

133
00:09:56,471 --> 00:09:58,962
I certainly can.

134
00:09:59,474 --> 00:10:02,010
I also understand
why your people in Denver...

135
00:10:02,226 --> 00:10:04,514
...left it for you to tell me.

136
00:10:05,687 --> 00:10:08,395
Obviously, some people
can be put off...

137
00:10:08,607 --> 00:10:12,692
...from staying in a place where
something like that happened.

138
00:10:12,903 --> 00:10:17,818
You can rest assured that's not
going to happen with me.

139
00:10:18,033 --> 00:10:21,697
And as far as my wife
is concerned...

140
00:10:21,870 --> 00:10:25,705
...I'm sure she'll be absolutely
fascinated when I tell her.

141
00:10:25,917 --> 00:10:28,750
She's a confirmed ghost story...

142
00:10:28,961 --> 00:10:31,374
...and horror film addict.

143
00:10:36,219 --> 00:10:39,927
Tony, do you think Dad'll get the job?

144
00:10:41,349 --> 00:10:43,556
<i>He already did.</i>

145
00:10:43,976 --> 00:10:47,720
<i>He's going to phone Wendy up
in a few minutes to tell her.</i>

146
00:10:55,613 --> 00:10:57,399
[PHONE RINGING]

147
00:11:01,034 --> 00:11:02,196
Hello.

148
00:11:02,412 --> 00:11:05,073
-Hi, babe.
<i>-Hi, hon. How's it going?</i>

149
00:11:05,289 --> 00:11:08,908
Great. I'm at the hotel and
I still have a lot to go through.

150
00:11:09,085 --> 00:11:12,248
I don't think I can get home
before 9:00 or 10:00.

151
00:11:12,422 --> 00:11:13,912
Sounds like you got the job.

152
00:11:14,131 --> 00:11:16,840
Right. It's a beautiful place.

153
00:11:17,051 --> 00:11:19,167
You and Danny are going to love it.

154
00:11:20,638 --> 00:11:23,551
Tony, why don't you want to go
to the hotel?

155
00:11:23,807 --> 00:11:25,548
<i>I don't know.</i>

156
00:11:26,602 --> 00:11:30,140
You do too know.
Now come on, tell me.

157
00:11:30,731 --> 00:11:32,769
<i>I don't want to.</i>

158
00:11:33,484 --> 00:11:34,769
Please.

159
00:11:35,986 --> 00:11:37,101
<i>No.</i>

160
00:11:37,447 --> 00:11:39,528
Now, Tony, tell me.

161
00:12:09,437 --> 00:12:12,144
DOCTOR: <i>Now, hold your eyes still
so I can see.</i>

162
00:12:16,653 --> 00:12:18,860
That's good. Now the other one.

163
00:12:20,280 --> 00:12:21,736
Good boy.

164
00:12:29,081 --> 00:12:30,447
Now, Danny...

165
00:12:30,917 --> 00:12:32,953
...when you were brushing
your teeth...

166
00:12:33,168 --> 00:12:36,161
...do you remember if you
smelled anything funny...

167
00:12:36,338 --> 00:12:41,129
...or saw any bright, flashing
lights or anything at all strange?

168
00:12:43,971 --> 00:12:45,133
No.

169
00:12:46,182 --> 00:12:48,673
DOCTOR: Do you remember
when you were brushing your teeth?

170
00:12:49,269 --> 00:12:50,554
Yes.

171
00:12:51,687 --> 00:12:55,351
What's the next thing you remember
after you were brushing your teeth?

172
00:12:59,528 --> 00:13:03,692
My mom was saying, "Wake up.
Wake up, Danny, wake up."

173
00:13:04,408 --> 00:13:08,619
Now, Danny, can you remember
what you were doing...

174
00:13:08,830 --> 00:13:11,743
...just before you started
brushing your teeth?

175
00:13:14,251 --> 00:13:16,038
Talking to Tony.

176
00:13:16,712 --> 00:13:19,044
Is Tony one of your animals?

177
00:13:19,923 --> 00:13:22,881
No. He's a little boy
that lives in my mouth.

178
00:13:23,177 --> 00:13:25,543
Tony's his imaginary friend.

179
00:13:25,971 --> 00:13:27,006
DOCTOR:
Oh.

180
00:13:28,515 --> 00:13:31,884
If you were to open your mouth now,
could I see Tony?

181
00:13:32,687 --> 00:13:34,097
No.

182
00:13:34,563 --> 00:13:35,803
Why not?

183
00:13:37,066 --> 00:13:38,898
Because he hides.

184
00:13:39,652 --> 00:13:41,312
Where does he go?

185
00:13:42,404 --> 00:13:44,236
To my stomach.

186
00:13:46,241 --> 00:13:49,154
Does Tony ever tell you
to do things?

187
00:13:53,249 --> 00:13:55,911
I don't want to talk
about Tony anymore.

188
00:13:56,711 --> 00:13:58,371
Okay.

189
00:13:58,546 --> 00:13:59,956
That's fine.

190
00:14:00,756 --> 00:14:02,543
All right, Danny.

191
00:14:03,342 --> 00:14:06,130
I'm going to ask you
to do me a favor...

192
00:14:06,346 --> 00:14:09,714
...and stay quietly in bed
for the rest of the day. Okay?

193
00:14:09,932 --> 00:14:11,047
Do I have to?

194
00:14:11,267 --> 00:14:13,508
Yes. I'd like you to.

195
00:14:13,727 --> 00:14:16,470
We're going in the other room
for a few minutes and talk.

196
00:14:16,688 --> 00:14:19,056
I'll come back and check on you.

197
00:14:19,232 --> 00:14:21,099
-Okay.
-Bye.

198
00:14:27,325 --> 00:14:29,736
-Shall we go into the living room?
-Yes.

199
00:14:33,456 --> 00:14:35,288
-Please.
-Thank you.

200
00:14:39,169 --> 00:14:43,538
Mrs. Torrance, I don't think
you have anything to worry about.

201
00:14:43,758 --> 00:14:47,797
I'm quite sure there's nothing
physically wrong with Danny.

202
00:14:48,471 --> 00:14:49,961
Yeah?

203
00:14:50,431 --> 00:14:51,966
Oh.

204
00:14:52,517 --> 00:14:55,600
He seems absolutely fine now.

205
00:14:55,686 --> 00:14:57,142
But you should've seen him.

206
00:14:57,522 --> 00:14:58,557
I know.

207
00:14:58,773 --> 00:15:00,480
Kids can scare you to death.

208
00:15:00,649 --> 00:15:03,517
But believe me, these episodes
are not at all uncommon.

209
00:15:03,735 --> 00:15:06,318
And they look much worse
than they are.

210
00:15:06,822 --> 00:15:09,485
But what was the matter with him?

211
00:15:09,700 --> 00:15:13,818
Most of the time, these episodes
with kids are never explained.

212
00:15:13,995 --> 00:15:18,865
They're brought on by emotional
factors and rarely occur again.

213
00:15:19,668 --> 00:15:22,661
They're more akin
to autohypnosis...

214
00:15:22,838 --> 00:15:25,831
...a kind of self-induced trance.

215
00:15:26,008 --> 00:15:27,999
If it reoccurs, which I doubt...

216
00:15:28,885 --> 00:15:32,004
...we can always think about
having some tests done.

217
00:15:32,472 --> 00:15:33,928
No, thank you.

218
00:15:34,600 --> 00:15:36,841
I'm sure you're right.

219
00:15:38,520 --> 00:15:41,182
Have you been in Boulder long?

220
00:15:42,024 --> 00:15:43,309
Only about three months.

221
00:15:43,525 --> 00:15:46,860
We're from Vermont. My husband
was teaching school there.

222
00:15:48,865 --> 00:15:52,698
Did the appearance
of Danny's imaginary friend....

223
00:15:52,951 --> 00:15:53,942
Tony.

224
00:15:54,162 --> 00:15:58,120
Did Tony's first appearance happen
to coincide with your arrival here?

225
00:15:59,332 --> 00:16:01,039
No, um....

226
00:16:01,210 --> 00:16:02,541
Let's see....

227
00:16:03,254 --> 00:16:05,836
I guess Danny started
talking to Tony...

228
00:16:06,048 --> 00:16:08,710
...about the time we put him
in nursery school.

229
00:16:09,134 --> 00:16:11,422
Did he adjust well to school?

230
00:16:12,304 --> 00:16:13,466
No.

231
00:16:13,639 --> 00:16:15,549
He didn't like it too much at first.

232
00:16:15,765 --> 00:16:19,053
Then he had an injury, so we kept
him out for a while and....

233
00:16:19,769 --> 00:16:24,389
Yeah, I guess that's about when I first
noticed he was talking to Tony.

234
00:16:25,400 --> 00:16:27,768
What sort of injury did he have?

235
00:16:28,446 --> 00:16:30,607
He dislocated his shoulder.

236
00:16:31,072 --> 00:16:33,360
How did he manage to do that?

237
00:16:36,787 --> 00:16:39,870
It was just one of
those things, you know.

238
00:16:40,081 --> 00:16:42,072
Purely an accident.

239
00:16:43,043 --> 00:16:45,831
My husband had been drinking...

240
00:16:46,047 --> 00:16:49,380
...and he came home
about three hours late.

241
00:16:49,674 --> 00:16:54,259
So he wasn't exactly
in the greatest mood that night.

242
00:16:54,971 --> 00:16:59,761
And Danny had scattered some of his
school papers all over the room...

243
00:16:59,936 --> 00:17:04,270
...and my husband grabbed his arm
to pull him away from them.

244
00:17:04,440 --> 00:17:07,522
It's just the sort of thing you do
100 times with a child...

245
00:17:07,734 --> 00:17:09,771
...you know, in a park or in the street.

246
00:17:10,863 --> 00:17:13,480
But on this particular occasion...

247
00:17:13,699 --> 00:17:16,316
...my husband just used
too much strength...

248
00:17:16,536 --> 00:17:19,118
...and he injured Danny's arm.

249
00:17:22,165 --> 00:17:26,705
Anyway, something good did come out
of it all because he said:

250
00:17:26,962 --> 00:17:29,500
"Wendy, I'm never going to
touch another drop.

251
00:17:29,714 --> 00:17:31,625
And if I do, you can leave me."

252
00:17:31,842 --> 00:17:33,173
And he didn't.

253
00:17:33,385 --> 00:17:37,880
He hasn't had any alcohol in 5 months.

254
00:18:03,164 --> 00:18:04,654
Boy.

255
00:18:04,834 --> 00:18:08,998
We must really be high up.
The air feels so different.

256
00:18:10,213 --> 00:18:11,670
Mm-hm.

257
00:18:14,634 --> 00:18:15,840
Dad?

258
00:18:16,429 --> 00:18:18,010
Yes?

259
00:18:18,681 --> 00:18:20,342
I'm hungry.

260
00:18:22,183 --> 00:18:24,925
You should've eaten your breakfast.

261
00:18:25,770 --> 00:18:28,683
We'll get you something
as soon as we get to the hotel.

262
00:18:28,857 --> 00:18:30,519
Okay, Mom.

263
00:18:31,943 --> 00:18:36,063
Wasn't it around here that
the Donner party got snowbound?

264
00:18:37,825 --> 00:18:41,159
I think that was farther west,
in the Sierras.

265
00:18:41,328 --> 00:18:42,615
Oh.

266
00:18:42,788 --> 00:18:45,200
What was the Donner party?

267
00:18:47,167 --> 00:18:51,412
They were a party of settlers
in covered wagon times.

268
00:18:51,672 --> 00:18:54,914
They got snowbound one winter
in the mountains.

269
00:18:55,134 --> 00:18:59,344
They had to resort to cannibalism
in order to stay alive.

270
00:19:00,472 --> 00:19:03,385
You mean they ate each other up?

271
00:19:03,558 --> 00:19:06,676
They had to in order to survive.

272
00:19:06,895 --> 00:19:08,102
Jack.

273
00:19:08,314 --> 00:19:09,394
Don't worry, Mom.

274
00:19:09,606 --> 00:19:13,942
I know all about cannibalism.
I saw it on TV.

275
00:19:14,153 --> 00:19:16,769
See, it's okay.

276
00:19:16,989 --> 00:19:19,401
He saw it on the television.

277
00:19:50,105 --> 00:19:51,938
-What time does the plane leave?
-8:30.

278
00:19:52,148 --> 00:19:54,936
That gives us plenty of time
to go over everything.

279
00:19:55,111 --> 00:19:57,067
-Goodbye, Mr. Ullman.
-Bye.

280
00:19:57,278 --> 00:20:00,396
Good morning. I hope you
haven't been waiting too long.

281
00:20:00,615 --> 00:20:03,232
No problem. We had time
to grab a bite to eat.

282
00:20:03,451 --> 00:20:06,318
Good. Glad you made it
before they shut down the kitchen.

283
00:20:06,538 --> 00:20:08,279
-Hi.
-Is your family having a look around?

284
00:20:08,457 --> 00:20:11,825
No, my son's
discovered the games room.

285
00:20:12,044 --> 00:20:14,160
-Has your luggage been brought in?
-Right there.

286
00:20:14,337 --> 00:20:15,577
Oh, fine.

287
00:20:15,756 --> 00:20:17,666
In view of all we have to cover today...

288
00:20:17,883 --> 00:20:21,547
...I suggest we have a quick look
at your apartment and get started.

289
00:20:21,761 --> 00:20:24,253
Have the Torrances' things
brought to their apartment.

290
00:20:24,432 --> 00:20:26,638
-Fine.
-I'd better collect my family first.

291
00:20:26,808 --> 00:20:28,048
Oh, yes.

292
00:20:35,567 --> 00:20:37,934
This is our Colorado Lounge.

293
00:20:38,153 --> 00:20:40,566
It's beautiful.

294
00:20:40,990 --> 00:20:42,822
My God!

295
00:20:43,032 --> 00:20:45,615
This place is fantastic, isn't it, hon?

296
00:20:45,827 --> 00:20:47,159
It sure is.

297
00:20:47,328 --> 00:20:50,162
I've never seen anything
like this before.

298
00:20:51,791 --> 00:20:53,749
Are all these
Indian designs authentic?

299
00:20:53,961 --> 00:20:55,372
I believe they're based...

300
00:20:55,587 --> 00:20:58,797
...mainly on Navajo and Apache motifs.

301
00:20:59,008 --> 00:21:00,964
They're really gorgeous.

302
00:21:01,176 --> 00:21:02,166
As a matter of fact...

303
00:21:02,385 --> 00:21:05,503
...this is probably the most
gorgeous hotel I've ever seen.

304
00:21:05,890 --> 00:21:08,847
This old place has had
an illustrious past.

305
00:21:09,058 --> 00:21:12,176
In its heyday, it was a stopping
place for the jet setters...

306
00:21:12,354 --> 00:21:15,346
...even before anybody knew
what a jet set was.

307
00:21:15,523 --> 00:21:18,606
We had four presidents
who stayed here.

308
00:21:18,861 --> 00:21:20,146
Lots of movie stars.

309
00:21:20,362 --> 00:21:21,897
Royalty?

310
00:21:22,280 --> 00:21:23,692
All the best people.

311
00:22:16,794 --> 00:22:19,376
This is the staff wing of the hotel.

312
00:22:20,338 --> 00:22:23,673
None of the other bedrooms
are heated during the winter.

313
00:22:23,925 --> 00:22:26,792
-Goodbye, Mr. Ullman.
-Goodbye, girls.

314
00:22:27,054 --> 00:22:29,045
ULLMAN:
And here are your quarters.

315
00:22:29,431 --> 00:22:32,048
Living room, bedroom, bathroom.

316
00:22:32,268 --> 00:22:34,759
And a small bedroom for your son.

317
00:22:38,356 --> 00:22:40,097
Perfect for a child.

318
00:22:40,276 --> 00:22:41,982
-Yeah.
-Yes.

319
00:22:47,615 --> 00:22:51,075
ULLMAN: Well, then. Place is
very nicely self-contained.

320
00:22:51,287 --> 00:22:52,823
Easy to keep.

321
00:22:55,624 --> 00:22:56,659
Cozy.

322
00:22:56,875 --> 00:22:59,116
ULLMAN:
Yes, very cozy for a family.

323
00:22:59,377 --> 00:23:01,038
If you feel like spreading out...

324
00:23:01,255 --> 00:23:03,916
...you have the rest of the hotel
to move around in.

325
00:23:05,550 --> 00:23:08,042
Well, it's very...

326
00:23:08,596 --> 00:23:09,882
...homey.

327
00:23:10,138 --> 00:23:11,253
Yeah.

328
00:23:12,807 --> 00:23:15,048
This is our famous hedge maze.

329
00:23:15,269 --> 00:23:19,557
It's quite an attraction here.
The walls are 13 feet high...

330
00:23:19,772 --> 00:23:22,059
...and the hedge is as old
as the hotel itself.

331
00:23:22,276 --> 00:23:24,893
A lot of fun, but I wouldn't
want to go in there...

332
00:23:25,112 --> 00:23:28,104
...unless I had an hour
to spare to find my way out.

333
00:23:29,490 --> 00:23:31,606
WENDY:
When was the Overlook built?

334
00:23:32,619 --> 00:23:34,826
Construction started in 1907.

335
00:23:35,038 --> 00:23:36,996
It was finished in 1909.

336
00:23:37,207 --> 00:23:39,868
The site's supposed to be
on an Indian burial ground.

337
00:23:40,085 --> 00:23:41,701
They actually had to repel...

338
00:23:41,921 --> 00:23:44,834
...a few Indian attacks as they
were building it.

339
00:23:45,423 --> 00:23:47,335
That's our Snowcat.

340
00:23:48,009 --> 00:23:49,340
Can you both drive a car?

341
00:23:49,510 --> 00:23:50,500
BOTH:
Yes.

342
00:23:50,679 --> 00:23:54,172
ULLMAN: That's fine. Basically
the Snowcat operates very much like a car.

343
00:23:54,349 --> 00:23:56,932
It won't take you long
to get the hang of it.

344
00:23:58,144 --> 00:24:01,512
As a matter of fact, we brought
a decorator in from Chicago...

345
00:24:01,690 --> 00:24:04,227
...just last year to refurbish
this part of the hotel.

346
00:24:04,401 --> 00:24:07,018
Oh. He sure did a beautiful job.

347
00:24:07,195 --> 00:24:09,528
Pink and gold are my favorite colors.

348
00:24:10,365 --> 00:24:12,698
Well, this is our Gold Ballroom.

349
00:24:13,451 --> 00:24:15,534
Oh, I'll say!

350
00:24:15,746 --> 00:24:19,535
We can accommodate up to
300 people here very comfortably.

351
00:24:20,041 --> 00:24:22,909
Boy, we could really have
a good party in this room.

352
00:24:23,127 --> 00:24:26,916
I'm afraid you won't do too well
here unless you brought supplies.

353
00:24:27,132 --> 00:24:30,214
We remove the booze from
the premises when we shut down.

354
00:24:30,385 --> 00:24:33,469
That reduces the insurance
we normally have to carry.

355
00:24:33,638 --> 00:24:34,628
We don't drink.

356
00:24:34,847 --> 00:24:36,259
Then you're in luck.

357
00:24:36,474 --> 00:24:40,719
Dick, come on over and say hello
to Mr. and Mrs. Torrance.

358
00:24:40,895 --> 00:24:43,057
This is Dick Hallorann,
our head chef.

359
00:24:43,231 --> 00:24:45,973
Mr. Hallorann, I'm Jack.
This is my wife, Winifred.

360
00:24:46,192 --> 00:24:47,398
Glad to meet you.

361
00:24:47,568 --> 00:24:50,435
The Torrances will take care
of the Overlook this winter.

362
00:24:50,655 --> 00:24:54,398
That's just great. How do you
folks like our hotel so far?

363
00:24:54,576 --> 00:24:56,442
It's just wonderful.

364
00:24:56,662 --> 00:24:58,198
Hi, Danny!

365
00:24:59,414 --> 00:25:01,781
I found him outside looking for you.

366
00:25:02,041 --> 00:25:05,705
Dan, did you get tired
of bombing the universe?

367
00:25:05,878 --> 00:25:07,085
Yeah.

368
00:25:07,256 --> 00:25:08,416
Come on over here.

369
00:25:08,589 --> 00:25:10,125
-Thanks.
-Thank you, Susie.

370
00:25:10,342 --> 00:25:14,336
I think it'd be good if you could
show Mrs. Torrance the kitchen...

371
00:25:14,555 --> 00:25:16,421
...while I continue on with Jack.

372
00:25:16,597 --> 00:25:19,056
It would be a pleasure. Right this way.

373
00:25:19,268 --> 00:25:20,804
Great. See you later, hon.

374
00:25:21,019 --> 00:25:22,384
Bye, darling.

375
00:25:24,772 --> 00:25:28,106
Mrs. Torrance, your husband
introduced you as Winifred.

376
00:25:28,277 --> 00:25:30,814
Now, are you a "Winnie,"
or a "Freddie"?

377
00:25:31,029 --> 00:25:32,019
I'm a Wendy.

378
00:25:32,197 --> 00:25:35,690
Oh, Wendy. That's nice.
That's the prettiest.

379
00:25:35,909 --> 00:25:37,525
This is the kitchen, huh?

380
00:25:37,744 --> 00:25:39,326
This is it.

381
00:25:39,538 --> 00:25:41,996
How do you like it, Danny?
Is it big enough for you?

382
00:25:42,165 --> 00:25:45,500
Yeah. It's the biggest place I ever seen.

383
00:25:45,752 --> 00:25:48,085
This whole place
is such an enormous maze.

384
00:25:48,297 --> 00:25:51,835
I'll have to leave a trail of
breadcrumbs every time I come in.

385
00:25:52,759 --> 00:25:54,625
Don't let it get you down.

386
00:25:54,802 --> 00:25:57,295
It's big, but it ain't
nothing but a kitchen.

387
00:25:57,513 --> 00:25:59,721
A lot of this stuff
you'll never have to touch.

388
00:25:59,932 --> 00:26:02,140
I wouldn't know
what to do with it if I did.

389
00:26:02,352 --> 00:26:05,470
One thing for sure, you don't
have to worry about food.

390
00:26:05,689 --> 00:26:10,354
You folks could eat here for a year
and never have the same menu twice.

391
00:26:10,568 --> 00:26:13,652
Right here is our walk-in freezer.

392
00:26:14,823 --> 00:26:17,861
This is where we keep
all of our meat.

393
00:26:18,076 --> 00:26:20,067
You got 15 rib roasts...

394
00:26:20,287 --> 00:26:22,403
...30 ten-pound bags of hamburger.

395
00:26:22,623 --> 00:26:25,661
We got 12 turkeys,
about 40 chickens...

396
00:26:25,875 --> 00:26:28,993
...50 sirloin steaks,
two dozen of pork roast...

397
00:26:29,171 --> 00:26:32,163
...and 20 legs of lamb.
Do you like lamb, Doc?

398
00:26:32,340 --> 00:26:34,001
-No.
-You don't?

399
00:26:34,175 --> 00:26:35,758
What's your favorite food, then?

400
00:26:35,969 --> 00:26:37,835
French fries and ketchup.

401
00:26:38,555 --> 00:26:40,546
I think we can
manage that too, Doc.

402
00:26:40,766 --> 00:26:42,507
Come along, now.
Watch your step.

403
00:26:46,188 --> 00:26:48,269
Mr. Hallorann...

404
00:26:49,232 --> 00:26:50,815
...how'd you know we call him Doc?

405
00:26:51,026 --> 00:26:55,019
-Beg your pardon?
-Doc. You called Danny "Doc" twice.

406
00:26:55,239 --> 00:26:57,276
-I did?
-Yeah.

407
00:26:57,449 --> 00:27:00,567
We call him Doc sometimes,
like in the Bugs Bunny cartoons.

408
00:27:00,786 --> 00:27:02,026
But how did you know?

409
00:27:02,246 --> 00:27:04,782
I guess I probably
heard you call him that.

410
00:27:04,998 --> 00:27:07,239
It's possible.
But I honestly don't remember...

411
00:27:07,459 --> 00:27:09,665
...calling him that
since we've been with you.

412
00:27:09,877 --> 00:27:12,039
Anyway, he looks
like a Doc, doesn't he?

413
00:27:12,256 --> 00:27:14,917
[IMITATES BUGS BUNNY]
Eh, what's up, Doc?

414
00:27:16,759 --> 00:27:18,967
Now, this is the storeroom.

415
00:27:20,721 --> 00:27:22,554
In here is where we keep...

416
00:27:22,723 --> 00:27:25,557
...all the dried goods
and the canned goods.

417
00:27:25,727 --> 00:27:28,184
We got canned fruits
and vegetables...

418
00:27:28,396 --> 00:27:32,185
...canned fish and meats,
hot and cold cereals.

419
00:27:32,401 --> 00:27:35,564
Post Toasties, Corn Flakes,
Sugar Puffs...

420
00:27:35,778 --> 00:27:39,817
...Rice Krispies, oatmeal,
Wheatena and Cream of Wheat.

421
00:27:40,075 --> 00:27:42,487
You got a dozen jugs
of black molasses.

422
00:27:42,702 --> 00:27:45,912
We got 60 boxes of dried milk....

423
00:27:49,542 --> 00:27:51,125
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

424
00:27:53,547 --> 00:27:56,005
DICK'S VOICE:
<i>How'd you like some ice cream, Doc?</i>

425
00:27:58,426 --> 00:28:00,417
DICK:
Sociables, finger rolls...

426
00:28:00,596 --> 00:28:02,132
...and 7 kinds of what have you.

427
00:28:02,346 --> 00:28:05,884
Now, we've got dried peaches,
dried apricots...

428
00:28:06,101 --> 00:28:09,183
...dried raisins and dried prunes.

429
00:28:09,395 --> 00:28:13,684
You know, you got to keep regular
if you want to be happy.

430
00:28:15,234 --> 00:28:16,441
-Hi.
WENDY: Hi.

431
00:28:16,612 --> 00:28:18,228
-How're you getting on?
-Fine.

432
00:28:18,446 --> 00:28:21,984
Can we borrow Mrs. Torrance?
We're on our way to the basement.

433
00:28:22,201 --> 00:28:24,112
I promise we won't
keep her very long.

434
00:28:24,327 --> 00:28:27,537
No problem, Mr. Ullman. I was just
getting to the ice cream.

435
00:28:27,748 --> 00:28:30,285
-You like ice cream, Doc?
-Yeah.

436
00:28:30,459 --> 00:28:31,449
I thought you did.

437
00:28:31,626 --> 00:28:34,710
You folks mind if I give Danny
some ice cream while we wait?

438
00:28:34,922 --> 00:28:36,753
-Not at all.
-We don't mind.

439
00:28:36,964 --> 00:28:38,625
-Good.
-Sound good to you, Doc?

440
00:28:38,799 --> 00:28:41,416
DANNY: Yeah.
-Okay, you behave yourself.

441
00:28:44,431 --> 00:28:46,297
What kind of ice cream do you like?

442
00:28:46,474 --> 00:28:47,509
Chocolate.

443
00:28:47,683 --> 00:28:50,550
Chocolate it shall be.
Come on, son.

444
00:28:55,150 --> 00:28:57,141
It's amazing, all this activity today.

445
00:28:57,318 --> 00:29:00,152
The guests and some staff
left yesterday, but the...

446
00:29:00,321 --> 00:29:01,778
...last day's always hectic.

447
00:29:01,990 --> 00:29:05,028
Everybody wants to be on their way
as early as possible.

448
00:29:05,243 --> 00:29:09,282
By 5:00 tonight, you'll never
know anybody was ever here.

449
00:29:09,498 --> 00:29:11,535
WENDY: Just like a ghost ship, huh?
-Yes.

450
00:29:17,213 --> 00:29:20,172
Do you know how I knew
your name was Doc?

451
00:29:26,765 --> 00:29:29,176
You know what I'm talking about,
don't you?

452
00:29:36,148 --> 00:29:39,642
I can remember when I was
a little boy...

453
00:29:40,028 --> 00:29:42,565
...my grandmother and I
could hold conversations...

454
00:29:42,780 --> 00:29:46,615
...entirely without ever
opening our mouths.

455
00:29:47,702 --> 00:29:49,990
She called it "shining."

456
00:29:51,498 --> 00:29:54,205
And for a long time I thought
it was just the two of us...

457
00:29:54,417 --> 00:29:57,035
...that had "the shine" to us.

458
00:29:57,671 --> 00:30:00,663
Just like you probably thought
you was the only one.

459
00:30:01,340 --> 00:30:03,207
But there are other folks...

460
00:30:03,384 --> 00:30:07,127
...though mostly they don't
know it, or don't believe it.

461
00:30:11,809 --> 00:30:14,221
How long have you
been able to do it?

462
00:30:19,442 --> 00:30:21,855
Why don't you want to talk about it?

463
00:30:27,075 --> 00:30:29,156
I'm not supposed to.

464
00:30:30,746 --> 00:30:33,238
Who says you ain't supposed to?

465
00:30:36,710 --> 00:30:38,075
Tony.

466
00:30:40,087 --> 00:30:41,749
Who's Tony?

467
00:30:44,217 --> 00:30:47,585
Tony's the little boy
that lives in my mouth.

468
00:30:49,556 --> 00:30:51,593
Is Tony the one that...

469
00:30:51,767 --> 00:30:53,348
...tells you things?

470
00:30:54,894 --> 00:30:56,477
Yes.

471
00:30:57,897 --> 00:31:00,265
How does he tell you things?

472
00:31:02,109 --> 00:31:06,398
It's like I go to sleep,
and he shows me things.

473
00:31:06,615 --> 00:31:10,700
But when I wake up,
I can't remember everything.

474
00:31:12,537 --> 00:31:16,246
Does your mom and dad
know about Tony?

475
00:31:17,500 --> 00:31:18,740
Yes.

476
00:31:19,544 --> 00:31:22,126
Do they know he tells you things?

477
00:31:22,963 --> 00:31:25,922
Tony told me never to tell them.

478
00:31:28,053 --> 00:31:31,421
Has Tony ever told you
anything about this place?

479
00:31:31,640 --> 00:31:34,176
About the Overlook Hotel?

480
00:31:37,479 --> 00:31:39,015
I don't know.

481
00:31:39,940 --> 00:31:42,227
Now think real hard, Doc.

482
00:31:42,317 --> 00:31:43,978
Think.

483
00:31:47,072 --> 00:31:49,814
Maybe he showed me something.

484
00:31:50,741 --> 00:31:53,358
Try to think of what it was.

485
00:31:56,373 --> 00:31:59,661
Mr. Hallorann, are you scared
of this place?

486
00:32:01,169 --> 00:32:02,625
No.

487
00:32:02,796 --> 00:32:05,002
Scared of nothing here.

488
00:32:05,507 --> 00:32:06,997
It's just that...

489
00:32:07,717 --> 00:32:10,549
...you know, some places
are like people.

490
00:32:11,387 --> 00:32:13,095
Some shine...

491
00:32:13,306 --> 00:32:14,671
...and some don't.

492
00:32:15,933 --> 00:32:18,049
I guess you could say
the Overlook Hotel...

493
00:32:18,269 --> 00:32:21,557
...has something about it
that's like shining.

494
00:32:24,608 --> 00:32:27,020
Is there something bad here?

495
00:32:35,077 --> 00:32:36,693
Well...

496
00:32:38,623 --> 00:32:41,035
...you know, Doc,
when something happens...

497
00:32:41,250 --> 00:32:44,868
...it can leave a trace
of itself behind.

498
00:32:45,672 --> 00:32:47,208
Say, like...

499
00:32:47,423 --> 00:32:50,507
...if someone burns toast.

500
00:32:51,219 --> 00:32:52,424
Well....

501
00:32:52,596 --> 00:32:57,260
Maybe things that happen
leave other kind of traces behind.

502
00:32:58,434 --> 00:33:01,894
Not things that anyone can notice.

503
00:33:02,063 --> 00:33:06,898
But things that people
who shine can see.

504
00:33:07,986 --> 00:33:11,273
Just like they can see things
that haven't happened yet...

505
00:33:11,615 --> 00:33:13,105
...well...

506
00:33:13,575 --> 00:33:17,739
...sometimes they can see things
that happened a long time ago.

507
00:33:19,247 --> 00:33:22,114
I think a lot of things
happened right here...

508
00:33:22,334 --> 00:33:26,042
...in this particular hotel
over the years.

509
00:33:26,587 --> 00:33:28,954
And not all of them was good.

510
00:33:32,259 --> 00:33:34,922
What about room 237?

511
00:33:38,266 --> 00:33:40,427
Room 237?

512
00:33:41,769 --> 00:33:44,853
You're scared of room 237, ain't you?

513
00:33:46,607 --> 00:33:48,097
No, I ain't.

514
00:33:49,611 --> 00:33:53,444
Mr. Hallorann, what is in room 237?

515
00:33:54,782 --> 00:33:56,114
Nothing.

516
00:33:56,576 --> 00:33:59,785
There ain't nothing in room 237.

517
00:33:59,996 --> 00:34:03,239
But you ain't got no business
going in there anyway.

518
00:34:03,458 --> 00:34:05,574
So stay out.

519
00:34:05,794 --> 00:34:08,286
You understand? Stay out!

520
00:34:14,135 --> 00:34:16,126
[WOLF HOWLS]

521
00:35:32,338 --> 00:35:33,750
[KNOCKING]

522
00:35:47,811 --> 00:35:49,552
Good morning, hon.

523
00:35:51,565 --> 00:35:53,306
Your breakfast is ready.

524
00:35:54,068 --> 00:35:55,730
What time is it?

525
00:35:55,903 --> 00:35:57,769
It's about 11:30.

526
00:35:58,239 --> 00:36:01,277
Eleven-thirty, Jesus.

527
00:36:02,242 --> 00:36:04,655
I guess we've been
staying up too late.

528
00:36:04,954 --> 00:36:06,409
I know it.

529
00:36:07,706 --> 00:36:10,574
I made them just the way
you like them, sunny-side up.

530
00:36:10,876 --> 00:36:12,413
Nice.

531
00:36:14,713 --> 00:36:16,500
It's really pretty outside.

532
00:36:16,715 --> 00:36:19,925
How about taking me for a walk
after you finish your breakfast?

533
00:36:20,552 --> 00:36:24,887
I suppose I ought to try
to do some writing first.

534
00:36:26,309 --> 00:36:27,969
Any ideas yet?

535
00:36:28,978 --> 00:36:30,639
Lots of ideas.

536
00:36:30,855 --> 00:36:32,391
No good ones.

537
00:36:32,856 --> 00:36:35,315
Something will come.

538
00:36:35,818 --> 00:36:39,777
It's just a matter of settling into
the habit of writing every day.

539
00:36:40,364 --> 00:36:43,027
Yep. That's all it is.

540
00:36:45,119 --> 00:36:47,452
It's really nice up here, isn't it?

541
00:36:47,831 --> 00:36:49,286
I love it.

542
00:36:49,791 --> 00:36:51,373
I really do.

543
00:36:52,293 --> 00:36:55,284
I've never been this happy
or comfortable anywhere.

544
00:36:55,505 --> 00:36:59,293
It's amazing how fast you get
used to such a big place.

545
00:36:59,467 --> 00:37:02,380
I tell you, when we first
came up here...

546
00:37:02,594 --> 00:37:04,632
...I thought it was kind of scary.

547
00:37:05,097 --> 00:37:07,635
I fell in love with it right away.

548
00:37:08,309 --> 00:37:11,141
When I came up here
for my interview...

549
00:37:11,478 --> 00:37:15,313
...it was as though
I'd been here before.

550
00:37:15,525 --> 00:37:18,141
I mean, we all have moments
of déjà vu...

551
00:37:18,360 --> 00:37:20,568
...but this was ridiculous.

552
00:37:21,322 --> 00:37:23,153
It was almost as though I knew...

553
00:37:23,365 --> 00:37:26,824
...what was going to be
around every corner.

554
00:37:26,994 --> 00:37:29,657
Ooh-woo-ooh.

555
00:37:31,081 --> 00:37:33,197
[THUDDING]

556
00:38:00,235 --> 00:38:03,445
The loser has to keep
America clean. How's that?

557
00:38:03,655 --> 00:38:06,193
-All right.
-And you're going to lose.

558
00:38:06,409 --> 00:38:09,527
And I'm going to get you.
You'd better run fast!

559
00:38:09,704 --> 00:38:12,492
[WENDY HUMS]

560
00:38:14,541 --> 00:38:15,702
Look out!

561
00:38:15,876 --> 00:38:17,742
I'm coming in close.

562
00:38:17,961 --> 00:38:20,202
DANNY:
Loser has to keep America clean.

563
00:38:20,380 --> 00:38:22,338
WENDY: Oh, no!
DANNY: Keep America clean.

564
00:38:22,509 --> 00:38:24,795
Okay. Danny, you win.

565
00:38:25,135 --> 00:38:27,467
Let's take the rest of this walking.

566
00:38:27,639 --> 00:38:29,675
-Okay.
-Whew.

567
00:38:30,016 --> 00:38:31,380
Give me your hand.

568
00:38:34,061 --> 00:38:35,847
Isn't it beautiful?

569
00:38:36,063 --> 00:38:37,054
Yeah.

570
00:38:53,581 --> 00:38:54,945
DANNY:
Dead end.

571
00:39:51,931 --> 00:39:54,047
WENDY:
Woo, we made it.

572
00:39:54,559 --> 00:39:56,846
-Isn't it beautiful?
DANNY: Yeah.

573
00:40:17,498 --> 00:40:19,329
It's so pretty.

574
00:40:19,666 --> 00:40:21,077
Yeah.

575
00:40:23,880 --> 00:40:26,621
I didn't think it was
going to be this big. Did you?

576
00:40:26,798 --> 00:40:28,039
Nope.

577
00:40:38,143 --> 00:40:40,510
WOMAN [ON TV]:
<i>Rutherford was serving a life sentence...</i>

578
00:40:40,730 --> 00:40:42,516
<i>...for a 1968 shooting.</i>

579
00:40:42,690 --> 00:40:46,557
<i>And the search continues
for that missing Aspen woman.</i>

580
00:40:46,777 --> 00:40:50,146
<i>Twenty-four-year-old Susan Robertson
has been missing 10 days.</i>

581
00:40:50,364 --> 00:40:53,072
<i>She disappeared on a hunting trip
with her husband.</i>

582
00:40:53,284 --> 00:40:56,072
<i>They may have to
call off the search...</i>

583
00:40:56,286 --> 00:40:58,824
<i>...if a predicted snowstorm
moves in tomorrow.</i>

584
00:40:59,039 --> 00:41:00,871
<i>It's so beautiful
in Denver today...</i>

585
00:41:01,083 --> 00:41:03,199
<i>...it's hard to believe
a snowstorm could be close.</i>

586
00:41:03,418 --> 00:41:05,659
<i>I want to go outside
and lie in the sun...</i>

587
00:41:05,880 --> 00:41:09,998
<i>...yet to our north, to our west,
it is snowing and cold.</i>

588
00:41:10,217 --> 00:41:11,378
<i>And it's moving...</i>

589
00:41:11,594 --> 00:41:14,757
<i>...right here towards Colorado
as we talk. It's incredible.</i>

590
00:43:05,123 --> 00:43:07,114
[TYPEWRITER KEYS CLACKING]

591
00:43:43,371 --> 00:43:44,827
Hi, hon.

592
00:43:48,416 --> 00:43:49,827
How's it going?

593
00:43:52,380 --> 00:43:53,541
Fine.

594
00:43:55,675 --> 00:43:57,210
Get a lot written today?

595
00:43:59,554 --> 00:44:01,135
Yes.

596
00:44:03,099 --> 00:44:06,842
Hey, the weather forecast
said it's going to snow tonight.

597
00:44:12,065 --> 00:44:14,398
What do you want me to do about it?

598
00:44:16,570 --> 00:44:18,733
Come on, hon.

599
00:44:19,072 --> 00:44:21,063
Don't be so grouchy.

600
00:44:21,492 --> 00:44:22,822
I'm not...

601
00:44:23,202 --> 00:44:24,407
...being grouchy.

602
00:44:24,579 --> 00:44:27,411
I just want to finish my work.

603
00:44:30,918 --> 00:44:33,284
Okay. I understand.

604
00:44:33,545 --> 00:44:36,128
I'll come back later
with a couple of sandwiches.

605
00:44:36,340 --> 00:44:38,797
Maybe you'll let me
read something then.

606
00:44:42,012 --> 00:44:43,094
Wendy...

607
00:44:43,306 --> 00:44:45,922
...let me explain something to you.

608
00:44:46,809 --> 00:44:50,677
When you come in and interrupt,
you're breaking my concentration.

609
00:44:50,896 --> 00:44:52,307
You're distracting me...

610
00:44:52,523 --> 00:44:55,936
...and it will then take me time
to get back to where I was.

611
00:44:56,152 --> 00:44:57,608
Understand?

612
00:44:59,405 --> 00:45:00,610
Yeah.

613
00:45:01,072 --> 00:45:02,233
Fine.

614
00:45:03,409 --> 00:45:05,115
We're going to make a new rule:

615
00:45:05,327 --> 00:45:06,784
Whenever I'm in here...

616
00:45:06,954 --> 00:45:08,536
...and you hear me typing...

617
00:45:08,706 --> 00:45:10,195
[PUNCHES KEYS]

618
00:45:11,041 --> 00:45:13,954
...or whatever the fuck
you hear me doing in here...

619
00:45:14,170 --> 00:45:16,456
...when I'm in here,
that means I am working.

620
00:45:16,672 --> 00:45:18,913
That means don't come in.

621
00:45:19,132 --> 00:45:21,373
Now, do you think
you can handle that?

622
00:45:24,054 --> 00:45:25,465
Yeah.

623
00:45:26,014 --> 00:45:27,130
Fine.

624
00:45:28,184 --> 00:45:31,472
Why don't you start right now
and get the fuck out of here?

625
00:45:35,233 --> 00:45:36,643
Okay.

626
00:46:04,344 --> 00:46:05,335
[DANNY LAUGHING]

627
00:46:07,431 --> 00:46:08,795
WENDY:
All right, you!

628
00:46:10,226 --> 00:46:12,012
I know you've got more.

629
00:46:14,146 --> 00:46:15,181
Missed!

630
00:46:20,777 --> 00:46:21,768
DANNY:
Don't have!

631
00:46:21,945 --> 00:46:23,561
WENDY:
No fair anymore.

632
00:47:00,900 --> 00:47:02,891
[TYPEWRITER KEYS CLACKING]

633
00:47:20,588 --> 00:47:22,295
Oh, no.

634
00:47:31,264 --> 00:47:32,550
I knew it.

635
00:48:02,797 --> 00:48:06,289
This is KDK 12 calling KDK 1.

636
00:48:08,802 --> 00:48:12,512
<i>KDK 12 to KDK 1.</i>

637
00:48:12,722 --> 00:48:15,840
This is KDK 1.
We're receiving you. Over.

638
00:48:16,226 --> 00:48:19,344
Hi, this is Wendy Torrance
at the Overlook Hotel.

639
00:48:19,938 --> 00:48:22,726
Hi, how are you folks
getting on up there? Over.

640
00:48:22,983 --> 00:48:24,313
We're just fine.

641
00:48:24,527 --> 00:48:26,985
But our telephones
aren't doing too well.

642
00:48:27,195 --> 00:48:30,233
Are the lines down,
by any chance? Over.

643
00:48:30,865 --> 00:48:34,655
Yes, quite a few of them are down
due to the storm. Over.

644
00:48:34,994 --> 00:48:38,077
<i>Any chance of them
being repaired soon? Over.</i>

645
00:48:38,164 --> 00:48:39,746
Well, I wouldn't like to say.

646
00:48:39,833 --> 00:48:43,168
Most winters they stay that way
until spring. Over.

647
00:48:43,670 --> 00:48:47,083
Boy, this storm is really something,
isn't it? Over.

648
00:48:47,550 --> 00:48:50,463
Yes. It's one of the worst
we've had for years.

649
00:48:51,010 --> 00:48:54,219
Is there anything else we can
do for you, Mrs. Torrance?

650
00:48:54,681 --> 00:48:56,844
I suppose not. Over.

651
00:48:57,476 --> 00:49:00,764
If you folks have any problems
up there, just give us a call.

652
00:49:00,980 --> 00:49:02,266
And, Mrs. Torrance?

653
00:49:02,481 --> 00:49:06,690
<i>It might be a good idea if you
leave your radio on all the time.</i>

654
00:49:07,527 --> 00:49:09,018
Okay. We'll do that.

655
00:49:09,195 --> 00:49:11,277
It was real nice talking to you.

656
00:49:11,489 --> 00:49:14,106
Bye. Over and out.

657
00:49:49,027 --> 00:49:51,235
GIRLS:
Hello, Danny.

658
00:49:56,494 --> 00:49:58,905
Come and play with us.

659
00:50:03,791 --> 00:50:06,579
Come and play with us, Danny.

660
00:50:08,422 --> 00:50:10,253
Forever...

661
00:50:12,050 --> 00:50:13,791
...and ever...

662
00:50:14,762 --> 00:50:16,753
...and ever.

663
00:50:48,253 --> 00:50:49,869
Tony...

664
00:50:50,880 --> 00:50:52,918
...I'm scared.

665
00:50:58,389 --> 00:51:01,972
<i>Remember what Mr. Hallorann said.</i>

666
00:51:03,561 --> 00:51:07,474
<i>It's just like pictures in a book, Danny.</i>

667
00:51:07,648 --> 00:51:09,809
<i>It isn't real.</i>

668
00:51:21,286 --> 00:51:23,119
<i>Please let me give you some money.</i>

669
00:51:23,329 --> 00:51:25,320
<i>I wouldn't think of it.</i>

670
00:51:25,583 --> 00:51:26,822
<i>Well, how can I repay you?</i>

671
00:51:27,835 --> 00:51:29,701
<i>It's okay. Really.</i>

672
00:51:30,336 --> 00:51:32,452
<i>Well, I'm going to have some coffee.</i>

673
00:51:32,672 --> 00:51:34,163
<i>Would you like some?</i>

674
00:51:35,925 --> 00:51:37,007
<i>Sure.</i>

675
00:51:37,177 --> 00:51:39,043
<i>Great. Sit down.</i>

676
00:51:48,021 --> 00:51:51,606
<i>Ooh, marvelous doughnuts.
Help yourself.</i>

677
00:51:53,235 --> 00:51:55,693
<i>-Coffee will be ready--</i>
DANNY: Mom.

678
00:51:57,530 --> 00:51:58,942
WENDY:
Yeah.

679
00:51:59,449 --> 00:52:02,784
DANNY: Can I go up to my room
and get my fire engine?

680
00:52:04,204 --> 00:52:06,945
WENDY:
Not right now. Daddy's asleep.

681
00:52:07,916 --> 00:52:10,077
DANNY:
I won't make any noise.

682
00:52:11,503 --> 00:52:13,369
WENDY:
Now come on, Doc.

683
00:52:13,588 --> 00:52:15,295
He only went to bed a few hours ago.

684
00:52:15,507 --> 00:52:17,293
Can't you wait till later?

685
00:52:17,509 --> 00:52:20,626
DANNY: I won't make a sound.
I promise I'll tiptoe.

686
00:52:22,556 --> 00:52:25,139
WENDY:
Well, all right.

687
00:52:25,351 --> 00:52:27,717
But really don't make a sound.

688
00:52:27,936 --> 00:52:29,425
DANNY:
I won't, Mom.

689
00:52:30,230 --> 00:52:31,971
Make sure you come right back...

690
00:52:32,190 --> 00:52:34,181
...because I'm going to
make lunch soon.

691
00:52:35,068 --> 00:52:37,811
-Okay?
DANNY: Okay, Mom.

692
00:53:27,079 --> 00:53:30,242
Can I go to my room
and get my fire engine?

693
00:53:33,960 --> 00:53:36,168
Come here for a minute first.

694
00:54:13,166 --> 00:54:14,998
How's it going, Doc?

695
00:54:16,335 --> 00:54:17,326
Okay.

696
00:54:19,547 --> 00:54:21,333
Having a good time?

697
00:54:23,427 --> 00:54:24,882
Yes, Dad.

698
00:54:27,806 --> 00:54:29,012
Good.

699
00:54:31,226 --> 00:54:33,387
I want you to have a good time.

700
00:54:34,103 --> 00:54:35,719
I am, Dad.

701
00:54:42,112 --> 00:54:43,773
Dad?

702
00:54:44,197 --> 00:54:45,653
Yes?

703
00:54:46,199 --> 00:54:47,985
Do you feel bad?

704
00:54:50,661 --> 00:54:52,152
No.

705
00:54:53,916 --> 00:54:56,202
I'm just a little bit tired.

706
00:54:57,795 --> 00:55:00,378
Then why don't you go to sleep?

707
00:55:03,925 --> 00:55:05,507
I can't.

708
00:55:06,969 --> 00:55:09,257
I got too much to do.

709
00:55:12,559 --> 00:55:14,048
Dad?

710
00:55:15,728 --> 00:55:17,311
Yes?

711
00:55:18,565 --> 00:55:20,851
Do you like this hotel?

712
00:55:24,195 --> 00:55:25,561
Yes.

713
00:55:26,864 --> 00:55:28,230
I do.

714
00:55:29,242 --> 00:55:30,574
I love it.

715
00:55:32,746 --> 00:55:34,077
Don't you?

716
00:55:36,458 --> 00:55:37,947
I guess so.

717
00:55:40,586 --> 00:55:41,793
Good.

718
00:55:45,007 --> 00:55:47,340
I want you to like it here.

719
00:55:51,306 --> 00:55:54,719
I wish we could stay here forever...

720
00:55:54,934 --> 00:55:56,721
...and ever...

721
00:55:57,396 --> 00:55:58,726
...and ever.

722
00:56:01,148 --> 00:56:02,434
Dad?

723
00:56:04,152 --> 00:56:05,186
What?

724
00:56:06,445 --> 00:56:09,563
You would never hurt Mommy or me,
would you?

725
00:56:15,038 --> 00:56:16,527
What do you mean?

726
00:56:21,628 --> 00:56:24,244
Did your mother ever say that to you?

727
00:56:24,922 --> 00:56:26,708
That I would hurt you?

728
00:56:27,467 --> 00:56:28,831
No, Dad.

729
00:56:31,012 --> 00:56:32,594
You sure?

730
00:56:33,139 --> 00:56:34,675
Yes, Dad.

731
00:56:39,478 --> 00:56:41,516
I love you, Danny.

732
00:56:42,733 --> 00:56:45,315
I love you more than anything else...

733
00:56:45,527 --> 00:56:48,110
...in the whole world...

734
00:56:48,864 --> 00:56:51,947
...and I would never do anything
to hurt you...

735
00:56:52,242 --> 00:56:53,481
...never.

736
00:56:54,327 --> 00:56:56,409
You know that, don't you?

737
00:56:56,579 --> 00:56:58,445
-Hm?
-Yes, Dad.

738
00:56:59,373 --> 00:57:00,489
Good.

739
00:57:06,130 --> 00:57:08,338
[WIND HOWLING]

740
00:57:10,927 --> 00:57:12,918
[DANNY IMITATING ENGINE NOISES]

741
00:57:41,958 --> 00:57:43,369
Mom?

742
00:58:01,186 --> 00:58:02,847
Mom?

743
00:58:28,422 --> 00:58:30,163
Mom, are you in there?

744
00:58:51,737 --> 00:58:54,103
[JACK SCREAMING]

745
00:59:16,802 --> 00:59:18,793
[JACK GROANS]

746
00:59:28,981 --> 00:59:30,972
[JACK SCREAMS]

747
00:59:33,903 --> 00:59:35,644
WENDY:
Jack!

748
00:59:37,114 --> 00:59:40,733
Jack? Jack!

749
00:59:44,081 --> 00:59:45,663
Jack!

750
00:59:49,418 --> 00:59:50,500
What happened?

751
00:59:50,670 --> 00:59:51,909
Honey...

752
00:59:52,797 --> 00:59:54,163
...what's wrong?

753
00:59:55,050 --> 00:59:57,007
Jack?

754
01:00:02,349 --> 01:00:03,760
I had the most...

755
01:00:03,974 --> 01:00:06,557
...terrible nightmare I ever had.

756
01:00:08,521 --> 01:00:11,434
-It was the most horrible dream.
-It's okay, it's okay now.

757
01:00:12,650 --> 01:00:14,016
Really.

758
01:00:18,280 --> 01:00:19,862
I dreamed that I...

759
01:00:20,074 --> 01:00:22,532
...that I killed you and Danny.

760
01:00:25,288 --> 01:00:27,528
But I didn't just kill you.

761
01:00:28,833 --> 01:00:31,576
I cut you up into little pieces.

762
01:00:34,255 --> 01:00:35,791
My God.

763
01:00:36,507 --> 01:00:39,045
I must be losing my mind.

764
01:00:41,346 --> 01:00:43,963
Everything's going to be all right.

765
01:00:46,059 --> 01:00:48,766
Come on. Let's get up off the floor.

766
01:00:55,652 --> 01:00:58,894
It's okay. There. Now sit up.

767
01:00:59,572 --> 01:01:00,858
It's okay.

768
01:01:01,949 --> 01:01:03,405
It's okay.

769
01:01:07,454 --> 01:01:08,661
Danny!

770
01:01:08,956 --> 01:01:10,914
Everything's okay!

771
01:01:11,083 --> 01:01:14,246
Just go play in your room for a while.

772
01:01:14,588 --> 01:01:16,670
Your dad's just got a headache.

773
01:01:17,965 --> 01:01:21,003
Danny, mind what I say.
Go play in your room.

774
01:01:22,971 --> 01:01:25,929
Honey, let me just go
get him out of here.

775
01:01:26,099 --> 01:01:27,635
I'll be right back.

776
01:01:28,059 --> 01:01:29,389
Danny.

777
01:01:29,561 --> 01:01:31,597
Why don't you mind me?

778
01:01:33,190 --> 01:01:35,931
Oh, Danny.

779
01:01:38,235 --> 01:01:40,068
Oh, my God.

780
01:01:41,280 --> 01:01:43,648
What happened to your neck?

781
01:01:44,451 --> 01:01:47,739
Danny, what happened to your neck?

782
01:01:48,246 --> 01:01:49,610
Huh?

783
01:02:16,690 --> 01:02:18,648
You did this to him...

784
01:02:19,110 --> 01:02:20,521
...didn't you?!

785
01:02:22,364 --> 01:02:24,445
You son of a bitch!

786
01:02:24,657 --> 01:02:26,489
You did this to him!

787
01:02:26,701 --> 01:02:28,157
Didn't you?!

788
01:02:29,496 --> 01:02:31,157
How could you?!

789
01:02:31,373 --> 01:02:33,114
How could you?!

790
01:02:40,673 --> 01:02:42,380
Oh.

791
01:02:54,103 --> 01:02:55,344
[GROANING]

792
01:04:02,963 --> 01:04:06,081
God! I'd give anything for a drink.

793
01:04:08,719 --> 01:04:11,586
I'd give my goddamn soul...

794
01:04:11,806 --> 01:04:14,297
...for just a glass of beer.

795
01:04:29,282 --> 01:04:30,771
Hi, Lloyd.

796
01:04:34,329 --> 01:04:36,740
A little slow tonight, isn't it?

797
01:04:41,628 --> 01:04:43,869
Yes, it is, Mr. Torrance.

798
01:04:45,965 --> 01:04:47,420
What will it be?

799
01:04:49,094 --> 01:04:52,052
I'm awfully glad
you asked me that, Lloyd...

800
01:04:52,262 --> 01:04:55,597
...because I just happen to have
two twenties...

801
01:04:55,809 --> 01:04:58,675
...and two tens
right here in my wallet.

802
01:04:58,894 --> 01:05:02,137
I was afraid they were
going to be there until next April.

803
01:05:02,856 --> 01:05:04,688
So here's what:

804
01:05:04,983 --> 01:05:07,315
You slip me a bottle of bourbon...

805
01:05:07,487 --> 01:05:10,320
...a little glass and some ice.

806
01:05:10,489 --> 01:05:12,527
You can do that, can't you, Lloyd?

807
01:05:12,992 --> 01:05:15,324
You're not too busy, are you?

808
01:05:15,911 --> 01:05:18,403
No, sir. I'm not busy at all.

809
01:05:18,914 --> 01:05:20,496
Good man.

810
01:05:20,791 --> 01:05:21,873
You set them up...

811
01:05:22,168 --> 01:05:25,001
...and I'll knock them back,
one by one.

812
01:05:26,172 --> 01:05:29,085
White man's burden, Lloyd, my man.

813
01:05:29,300 --> 01:05:31,461
White man's burden.

814
01:05:37,516 --> 01:05:38,677
Say, Lloyd...

815
01:05:38,851 --> 01:05:41,639
...it seems I'm temporarily light.

816
01:05:41,980 --> 01:05:44,391
How's my credit in this joint, anyway?

817
01:05:44,690 --> 01:05:47,023
Your credit's fine, Mr. Torrance.

818
01:05:47,735 --> 01:05:49,351
That's swell.

819
01:05:49,570 --> 01:05:51,277
I like you, Lloyd.

820
01:05:51,489 --> 01:05:53,150
I always liked you.

821
01:05:53,365 --> 01:05:55,697
You were always the best of them.

822
01:05:55,869 --> 01:05:58,235
Best goddamned bartender...

823
01:05:58,454 --> 01:06:01,367
...from Timbuktu to Portland, Maine.

824
01:06:01,583 --> 01:06:03,824
Or Portland, Oregon, for that matter.

825
01:06:04,085 --> 01:06:05,871
Thank you for saying so.

826
01:06:08,297 --> 01:06:12,838
Here's to five miserable months
on the wagon...

827
01:06:13,052 --> 01:06:17,090
...and all the irreparable harm
that it's caused me.

828
01:06:35,324 --> 01:06:37,782
How are things going, Mr. Torrance?

829
01:06:39,119 --> 01:06:41,737
Things could be better.

830
01:06:43,248 --> 01:06:45,990
Things could be
a whole lot better.

831
01:06:46,878 --> 01:06:49,210
I hope it's nothing serious.

832
01:06:49,505 --> 01:06:50,916
No.

833
01:06:52,217 --> 01:06:54,208
Nothing serious.

834
01:06:55,844 --> 01:06:58,427
Just a little problem with...

835
01:06:58,597 --> 01:07:01,760
...the old sperm bank upstairs.

836
01:07:01,934 --> 01:07:04,302
Nothing I can't handle, though.

837
01:07:04,521 --> 01:07:06,228
Thanks.

838
01:07:06,688 --> 01:07:07,679
Women.

839
01:07:07,898 --> 01:07:09,434
Can't live with them...

840
01:07:09,608 --> 01:07:11,440
...can't live without them.

841
01:07:14,655 --> 01:07:16,237
Words of wisdom, Lloyd.

842
01:07:16,449 --> 01:07:17,905
Words of...

843
01:07:18,117 --> 01:07:19,606
...wisdom.

844
01:07:31,130 --> 01:07:34,373
I never laid a hand on him,
goddamn it.

845
01:07:34,592 --> 01:07:36,208
I didn't.

846
01:07:38,262 --> 01:07:42,847
I wouldn't touch one hair
on his goddamn little head.

847
01:07:43,476 --> 01:07:46,594
I love the little son of a bitch.

848
01:07:48,188 --> 01:07:51,021
I'd do anything for him.

849
01:07:51,233 --> 01:07:54,021
Any fucking thing for him.

850
01:07:58,115 --> 01:08:00,652
But that bitch!

851
01:08:01,661 --> 01:08:03,367
As long as I live...

852
01:08:03,663 --> 01:08:07,030
...she'll never let me forget
what happened.

853
01:08:16,676 --> 01:08:19,509
I did hurt him once, okay?

854
01:08:19,845 --> 01:08:21,927
It was an accident.

855
01:08:22,222 --> 01:08:24,840
Completely unintentional.

856
01:08:26,101 --> 01:08:28,342
It could have happened to anybody.

857
01:08:30,064 --> 01:08:33,523
And it was three goddamn years ago!

858
01:08:33,734 --> 01:08:36,568
The little fucker had thrown all my
papers all over the floor.

859
01:08:36,779 --> 01:08:39,237
All I tried to do was pull him up.

860
01:08:42,034 --> 01:08:46,699
A momentary loss of
muscular coordination.

861
01:08:47,039 --> 01:08:48,246
I mean...

862
01:08:48,791 --> 01:08:52,328
...a few extra foot-pounds of energy...

863
01:08:52,545 --> 01:08:55,377
...per second, per second.

864
01:08:59,844 --> 01:09:00,925
WENDY:
Jack!

865
01:09:09,729 --> 01:09:11,310
Oh, Jack.

866
01:09:11,480 --> 01:09:13,391
Thank God you're here.

867
01:09:15,150 --> 01:09:16,436
Jack.

868
01:09:16,610 --> 01:09:18,818
There's someone else
in the hotel with us.

869
01:09:19,029 --> 01:09:21,567
There's a crazy woman
in one of the rooms.

870
01:09:21,740 --> 01:09:24,323
She tried to strangle Danny.

871
01:09:26,871 --> 01:09:29,238
Are you out of your fucking mind?

872
01:09:29,539 --> 01:09:31,029
No.

873
01:09:31,208 --> 01:09:32,744
It's the truth! Really.

874
01:09:32,918 --> 01:09:35,411
I swear it. Danny told me.

875
01:09:35,755 --> 01:09:37,621
He went up into one of the bedrooms.

876
01:09:37,840 --> 01:09:41,298
The door was open, and he saw this
crazy woman in the bathtub.

877
01:09:41,511 --> 01:09:43,842
She tried to strangle him!

878
01:09:47,557 --> 01:09:49,298
Which room was it?

879
01:09:52,229 --> 01:09:53,936
[MUSIC PLAYS ON TV]

880
01:09:56,943 --> 01:09:59,104
NEWS NARRATOR:
<i>From Channel 10 in Miami...</i>

881
01:09:59,278 --> 01:10:01,645
<i>...this is</i> Newswatch
<i>with Glenn Rinker...</i>

882
01:10:01,863 --> 01:10:06,073
<i>...Ann Bishop, and
the award-winning</i> Newswatch <i>team.</i>

883
01:10:06,411 --> 01:10:08,823
<i>Good evening. I'm Glenn Rinker,</i>
Newswatch Ten.

884
01:10:09,037 --> 01:10:12,155
<i>As Miami continues to swelter
in a record winter heat wave...</i>

885
01:10:12,375 --> 01:10:14,490
<i>...bringing temperatures to the 90s...</i>

886
01:10:14,711 --> 01:10:17,828
<i>...Central and Mountain states
are buried in snow.</i>

887
01:10:18,046 --> 01:10:22,041
<i>In Colorado, 10 inches of snow
fell in just a few hours tonight.</i>

888
01:10:22,260 --> 01:10:24,466
<i>Travel in the Rockies
is almost impossible.</i>

889
01:10:24,679 --> 01:10:27,636
<i>Airports are shut down, stranding
thousands of passengers.</i>

890
01:10:27,849 --> 01:10:29,760
<i>Highways are blocked
by snowdrifts.</i>

891
01:10:29,975 --> 01:10:31,716
<i>Railroad tracks are frozen.</i>

892
01:10:31,935 --> 01:10:33,972
<i>Officials in Colorado
tell</i> Newswatch...

893
01:10:34,146 --> 01:10:37,730
<i>...at least three have been killed
by exposure to freezing winds.</i>

894
01:10:37,942 --> 01:10:40,229
<i>The governor of Colorado is expected...</i>

895
01:10:40,444 --> 01:10:42,152
<i>...to declare a weather emergency.</i>

896
01:10:42,363 --> 01:10:44,194
<i>The National Guard
might be called out...</i>

897
01:10:44,282 --> 01:10:45,613
<i>...to clear streets and roads.</i>

898
01:10:45,824 --> 01:10:48,032
<i>Weather forecasters
predict more snow...</i>

899
01:10:48,243 --> 01:10:50,234
<i>...and heavy winds
tonight and tomorrow...</i>

900
01:10:50,454 --> 01:10:53,072
<i>...with temperatures dropping
well below zero.</i>

901
01:10:53,291 --> 01:10:56,283
<i>Back here in Florida,
we've got the opposite problem.</i>

902
01:10:56,502 --> 01:10:58,708
<i>The heat and humidity
are supposed to climb.</i>

903
01:10:58,921 --> 01:11:00,877
<i>Local beaches should be jammed.</i>

904
01:11:01,090 --> 01:11:03,127
<i>Our weather expert,
Walter Cronice...</i>

905
01:11:03,341 --> 01:11:06,585
<i>...will have the local forecast
later on</i> Newswatch.

906
01:11:06,762 --> 01:11:08,753
[HEART THUDDING]

907
01:15:26,855 --> 01:15:28,846
[WOMAN CACKLING]

908
01:16:26,539 --> 01:16:28,530
[RINGING]

909
01:16:39,177 --> 01:16:43,011
MAN [ON RECORDING]: <i>We're sorry.</i>
<i>Your call cannot be completed as dialed.</i>

910
01:16:43,349 --> 01:16:46,511
<i>If you need assistance,
please call the operator.</i>

911
01:16:57,363 --> 01:16:59,024
[KNOCKING]

912
01:17:02,076 --> 01:17:03,407
Jack?

913
01:17:03,743 --> 01:17:05,576
JACK:
Yes, it's me.

914
01:17:05,787 --> 01:17:07,198
Thank God.

915
01:17:11,877 --> 01:17:13,662
Did you find anything?

916
01:17:13,878 --> 01:17:16,587
No. Nothing at all.

917
01:17:17,216 --> 01:17:20,378
I didn't see one goddamn thing.

918
01:17:23,096 --> 01:17:26,590
You went into the room Danny said?
To 237?

919
01:17:26,809 --> 01:17:28,390
Yes, I did.

920
01:17:28,853 --> 01:17:30,639
And you didn't see anything at all?

921
01:17:30,854 --> 01:17:32,845
Absolutely nothing.

922
01:17:33,064 --> 01:17:34,305
How is he?

923
01:17:34,524 --> 01:17:36,310
He's still asleep.

924
01:17:36,734 --> 01:17:37,850
Good.

925
01:17:43,658 --> 01:17:46,742
I'm sure he'll be himself again
in the morning.

926
01:17:51,250 --> 01:17:53,742
Are you sure it was the right room?

927
01:17:53,918 --> 01:17:57,082
I mean, maybe Danny made a mistake.

928
01:17:57,297 --> 01:17:59,664
He must have gone in that room.

929
01:17:59,884 --> 01:18:02,546
The door was open,
the lights were on.

930
01:18:05,180 --> 01:18:07,512
I just don't understand it.

931
01:18:11,854 --> 01:18:14,891
What about those bruises on his neck?

932
01:18:17,067 --> 01:18:19,399
Somebody did that to him.

933
01:18:27,661 --> 01:18:29,117
I think...

934
01:18:30,788 --> 01:18:33,326
...he did it to himself.

935
01:18:39,340 --> 01:18:40,579
No.

936
01:18:41,257 --> 01:18:43,295
That's not possible.

937
01:18:45,804 --> 01:18:47,340
Wendy...

938
01:18:48,599 --> 01:18:52,262
...once you rule out his version
of what happened...

939
01:18:52,478 --> 01:18:55,095
...there is no other explanation.

940
01:18:55,564 --> 01:18:56,895
Is there?

941
01:18:59,275 --> 01:19:02,143
It wouldn't be that different
from the episode...

942
01:19:02,363 --> 01:19:05,730
...that he had before
we came up here.

943
01:19:05,949 --> 01:19:07,155
Would it?

944
01:19:09,494 --> 01:19:11,327
[WENDY CRIES]

945
01:19:12,664 --> 01:19:14,405
WENDY:
<i>Oh, Jack.</i>

946
01:19:15,083 --> 01:19:18,076
<i>Whatever the explanation is...</i>

947
01:19:21,506 --> 01:19:22,917
<i>...I think we...</i>

948
01:19:23,132 --> 01:19:25,841
<i>. ..have to get Danny out of here.</i>

949
01:19:30,640 --> 01:19:32,472
Get him out of here?

950
01:19:34,060 --> 01:19:35,346
Yes.

951
01:19:36,646 --> 01:19:38,354
You mean...

952
01:19:39,399 --> 01:19:41,356
...just leave the hotel?

953
01:19:42,403 --> 01:19:43,768
Yes.

954
01:19:50,368 --> 01:19:51,779
JACK:
<i>It is so...</i>

955
01:19:51,953 --> 01:19:54,365
...typical of you to create
a problem like this...

956
01:19:54,581 --> 01:19:57,118
...when I finally have a chance
to accomplish something!

957
01:19:57,333 --> 01:19:59,871
When I'm really into my work!

958
01:20:00,087 --> 01:20:04,046
I could really write my own ticket
if I went back now, couldn't I?

959
01:20:04,257 --> 01:20:08,001
Shoveling out driveways,
work in a car wash.

960
01:20:08,220 --> 01:20:10,301
-Any of that appeal to you?
-Jack...

961
01:20:10,471 --> 01:20:14,215
Wendy, I have let you fuck up my life
so far...

962
01:20:14,393 --> 01:20:18,056
...but I am not going to let you
fuck this up.

963
01:20:43,671 --> 01:20:46,413
[CAN RATTLING]

964
01:20:53,931 --> 01:20:57,220
[BALLROOM MUSIC PLAYING]

965
01:21:26,798 --> 01:21:28,789
[RINGING]

966
01:21:35,974 --> 01:21:37,885
MAN [ON PHONE]:
<i>Good evening. Forest Service.</i>

967
01:21:37,975 --> 01:21:40,262
Hello, my name is Dick Hallorann.

968
01:21:40,479 --> 01:21:42,890
I'm the head chef at
the Overlook Hotel.

969
01:21:43,106 --> 01:21:45,222
<i>Good evening.
What can I do for you?</i>

970
01:21:45,442 --> 01:21:48,979
I've been trying to make
an urgent phone call up there...

971
01:21:49,195 --> 01:21:52,484
...but the operator said
that the phone lines are down.

972
01:21:52,698 --> 01:21:56,317
A lot of lines around here
are down due to the storm.

973
01:21:56,494 --> 01:21:59,157
I hate to put you through
any trouble...

974
01:21:59,372 --> 01:22:02,615
...but there's a family up there
all by themselves with a young kid.

975
01:22:02,835 --> 01:22:04,496
And with this storm
and everything...

976
01:22:04,670 --> 01:22:07,582
...I'd appreciate it if you'd give
them a call on your radio...

977
01:22:07,797 --> 01:22:09,788
...just to see if everything's okay.

978
01:22:10,300 --> 01:22:11,586
I'll be glad to do that.

979
01:22:11,801 --> 01:22:14,590
Why don't you call me back
in about 20 minutes?

980
01:22:14,805 --> 01:22:16,841
<i>Thank you very much.
I'll do that.</i>

981
01:22:17,015 --> 01:22:18,470
All right, sir.

982
01:22:19,350 --> 01:22:22,342
[BALLROOM MUSIC PLAYS]

983
01:22:28,234 --> 01:22:30,225
[PEOPLE CHATTERING AND LAUGHING]

984
01:22:38,787 --> 01:22:40,743
Good evening, Mr. Torrance.

985
01:22:40,956 --> 01:22:42,412
Good evening.

986
01:23:06,981 --> 01:23:08,438
Hi, Lloyd.

987
01:23:08,649 --> 01:23:10,515
Been away, but now I'm back.

988
01:23:10,777 --> 01:23:12,518
Good evening, Mr. Torrance.

989
01:23:13,197 --> 01:23:14,186
It's good to see you.

990
01:23:14,405 --> 01:23:17,068
It's good to be back, Lloyd.

991
01:23:17,701 --> 01:23:19,408
What'll it be, sir?

992
01:23:20,244 --> 01:23:22,485
Hair of the dog that bit me.

993
01:23:23,916 --> 01:23:25,577
Bourbon on the rocks.

994
01:23:26,417 --> 01:23:27,783
That'll do her.

995
01:23:41,307 --> 01:23:43,595
No charge to you, Mr. Torrance.

996
01:23:45,020 --> 01:23:46,976
No charge?

997
01:23:47,605 --> 01:23:49,596
Your money's no good here.

998
01:23:55,279 --> 01:23:56,987
Orders from the house.

999
01:24:00,202 --> 01:24:02,694
Orders from the house.

1000
01:24:05,957 --> 01:24:07,948
Drink up, Mr. Torrance.

1001
01:24:10,127 --> 01:24:14,667
I'm the kind of man likes to know
who's buying their drinks, Lloyd.

1002
01:24:16,969 --> 01:24:19,926
It's not a matter that concerns you,
Mr. Torrance.

1003
01:24:20,137 --> 01:24:22,048
At least, not at this point.

1004
01:24:26,853 --> 01:24:29,265
Anything you say, Lloyd.

1005
01:24:29,689 --> 01:24:31,680
Anything you say.

1006
01:24:43,494 --> 01:24:44,484
Oh!

1007
01:24:44,662 --> 01:24:47,154
Oh, dear! I'm so sorry, sir.

1008
01:24:47,416 --> 01:24:49,703
-Oh.
-Oh, dear. Oh, dear.

1009
01:24:49,917 --> 01:24:52,284
I've made an awful mess
of your jacket, sir.

1010
01:24:52,462 --> 01:24:57,332
Oh, that's all right.
I've got plenty of jackets.

1011
01:24:57,551 --> 01:25:00,338
I'm afraid it's advocaat, sir.
It tends to stain.

1012
01:25:00,554 --> 01:25:01,668
Advocaat, is it?

1013
01:25:01,887 --> 01:25:04,050
Yes, sir. I think the best thing...

1014
01:25:04,265 --> 01:25:06,472
...is to come along
to the gentlemen's room...

1015
01:25:06,685 --> 01:25:09,176
...and we'll get
some water to it, sir.

1016
01:25:10,021 --> 01:25:13,355
Looks like you might have got a
spot of it on yourself...

1017
01:25:13,524 --> 01:25:14,515
...Jeevesy old boy.

1018
01:25:14,734 --> 01:25:17,898
That doesn't matter, sir.
You're the important one.

1019
01:25:18,195 --> 01:25:20,608
Awfully nice of you to say.

1020
01:25:21,033 --> 01:25:23,899
Of course, I intended to change
my jacket this evening...

1021
01:25:24,118 --> 01:25:26,359
...before the fish and goose soiree.

1022
01:25:26,579 --> 01:25:28,617
Very wise, sir. Very wise.

1023
01:25:28,832 --> 01:25:30,072
JACK:
Here. I'll just...

1024
01:25:31,126 --> 01:25:33,367
...hold this for you there,
Jeevesy.

1025
01:25:33,587 --> 01:25:35,372
Thank you, sir. Thank you.

1026
01:25:36,422 --> 01:25:40,041
Let's see if we can improve this
with a little water, sir.

1027
01:25:40,260 --> 01:25:41,546
All right. I'll just...

1028
01:25:41,720 --> 01:25:45,930
...set my bourbon and advocaat
down right there.

1029
01:25:46,515 --> 01:25:47,926
Won't keep you a moment.

1030
01:25:48,143 --> 01:25:49,554
Fine.

1031
01:25:52,605 --> 01:25:54,266
What do they call you, Jeevesy?

1032
01:25:54,483 --> 01:25:57,065
Grady, sir. Delbert Grady.

1033
01:26:01,823 --> 01:26:02,813
Grady?

1034
01:26:02,990 --> 01:26:04,197
Yes, sir.

1035
01:26:05,368 --> 01:26:06,699
Delbert Grady.

1036
01:26:06,912 --> 01:26:08,402
That's right, sir.

1037
01:26:14,377 --> 01:26:16,368
Uh....

1038
01:26:17,130 --> 01:26:18,586
Mr. Grady...

1039
01:26:19,341 --> 01:26:21,422
...haven't I seen you
somewhere before?

1040
01:26:21,635 --> 01:26:24,342
Why, no, sir. I don't believe so.

1041
01:26:31,395 --> 01:26:33,226
It's coming off now, sir.

1042
01:26:34,398 --> 01:26:35,637
Uh...

1043
01:26:38,150 --> 01:26:39,733
...Mr. Grady...

1044
01:26:41,238 --> 01:26:43,695
...weren't you once
the caretaker here?

1045
01:26:43,907 --> 01:26:46,694
Why, no, sir. I don't believe so.

1046
01:26:49,746 --> 01:26:53,079
You a married man, are you, Mr. Grady?

1047
01:26:53,291 --> 01:26:54,326
Yes, sir.

1048
01:26:54,501 --> 01:26:57,583
I have a wife and two daughters, sir.

1049
01:26:58,630 --> 01:27:00,119
And...

1050
01:27:01,800 --> 01:27:03,086
...where are they now?

1051
01:27:03,301 --> 01:27:07,340
They're somewhere around.
I'm not quite sure at the moment.

1052
01:27:15,479 --> 01:27:16,935
Mr. Grady.

1053
01:27:18,024 --> 01:27:20,435
You were the caretaker here.

1054
01:27:21,903 --> 01:27:23,894
I recognize you.

1055
01:27:25,282 --> 01:27:28,319
I saw your picture
in the newspapers.

1056
01:27:28,784 --> 01:27:30,525
You...

1057
01:27:30,996 --> 01:27:34,533
...chopped your wife and daughter
up into little bits.

1058
01:27:35,041 --> 01:27:36,452
And...

1059
01:27:37,085 --> 01:27:38,996
...then you blew your brains out.

1060
01:27:48,930 --> 01:27:50,671
That's strange, sir.

1061
01:27:51,682 --> 01:27:54,425
I don't have any recollection
of that at all.

1062
01:27:58,105 --> 01:27:59,971
Mr. Grady...

1063
01:28:00,399 --> 01:28:03,734
...you were the caretaker here.

1064
01:28:11,536 --> 01:28:14,323
I'm sorry to differ with you, sir.

1065
01:28:16,207 --> 01:28:17,914
But you...

1066
01:28:18,667 --> 01:28:20,500
...are the caretaker.

1067
01:28:22,756 --> 01:28:25,668
You've always been the caretaker.

1068
01:28:28,552 --> 01:28:30,385
I should know, sir.

1069
01:28:31,847 --> 01:28:34,430
I've always been here.

1070
01:28:52,661 --> 01:28:54,868
Did you know, Mr. Torrance...

1071
01:28:55,079 --> 01:28:56,865
...that your son...

1072
01:28:57,248 --> 01:28:59,957
...is attempting to bring
an outside party...

1073
01:29:00,167 --> 01:29:02,375
...into this situation?

1074
01:29:04,922 --> 01:29:06,630
Did you know that?

1075
01:29:10,427 --> 01:29:11,417
No.

1076
01:29:12,889 --> 01:29:14,970
He is, Mr. Torrance.

1077
01:29:17,310 --> 01:29:18,470
Who?

1078
01:29:20,729 --> 01:29:22,345
A nigger.

1079
01:29:26,444 --> 01:29:27,809
A nigger?

1080
01:29:30,573 --> 01:29:31,984
A nigger...

1081
01:29:32,199 --> 01:29:33,280
...cook.

1082
01:29:39,791 --> 01:29:41,077
How?

1083
01:29:43,336 --> 01:29:45,122
Your son...

1084
01:29:45,546 --> 01:29:48,335
...has a very great talent.

1085
01:29:49,301 --> 01:29:52,793
I don't think you are aware
how great it is.

1086
01:29:53,555 --> 01:29:56,797
But he is attempting to use
that very talent...

1087
01:29:56,975 --> 01:29:58,966
...against your will.

1088
01:30:07,484 --> 01:30:08,770
Well...

1089
01:30:11,530 --> 01:30:14,613
...he is a very willful boy.

1090
01:30:16,994 --> 01:30:19,407
Indeed he is, Mr. Torrance.

1091
01:30:19,622 --> 01:30:22,489
A very willful boy.

1092
01:30:22,708 --> 01:30:24,039
A rather...

1093
01:30:24,252 --> 01:30:25,787
...naughty boy...

1094
01:30:26,003 --> 01:30:29,167
...if I may be so bold, sir.

1095
01:30:36,430 --> 01:30:38,171
It's his mother.

1096
01:30:40,351 --> 01:30:41,807
She...

1097
01:30:42,020 --> 01:30:44,011
...interferes.

1098
01:30:47,108 --> 01:30:50,190
Perhaps they need a good...

1099
01:30:50,403 --> 01:30:52,019
...talking-to.

1100
01:30:52,447 --> 01:30:53,481
If...

1101
01:30:53,657 --> 01:30:56,239
...you don't mind my saying so.

1102
01:30:57,034 --> 01:30:58,695
Perhaps...

1103
01:30:59,203 --> 01:31:00,911
...a bit more.

1104
01:31:04,125 --> 01:31:05,364
My girls, sir...

1105
01:31:05,542 --> 01:31:09,377
...they didn't care for
the Overlook at first.

1106
01:31:10,047 --> 01:31:13,916
One of them actually stole
a pack of matches...

1107
01:31:14,135 --> 01:31:16,796
...and tried to burn it down.

1108
01:31:17,889 --> 01:31:19,550
But I...

1109
01:31:19,724 --> 01:31:21,715
...corrected them, sir.

1110
01:31:23,060 --> 01:31:27,180
And when my wife tried to prevent me
from doing my duty...

1111
01:31:27,399 --> 01:31:28,639
...I...

1112
01:31:29,650 --> 01:31:31,733
...corrected her.

1113
01:31:45,958 --> 01:31:47,916
We have the Snowcat.

1114
01:31:51,296 --> 01:31:53,082
If the weather breaks...

1115
01:31:53,257 --> 01:31:55,043
...we might just be able...

1116
01:31:55,260 --> 01:31:57,091
...to get down the mountain.

1117
01:31:58,179 --> 01:31:59,795
[HEART THUDDING]

1118
01:31:59,972 --> 01:32:02,930
I could call
the forest rangers first...

1119
01:32:03,143 --> 01:32:04,429
...and...

1120
01:32:04,769 --> 01:32:06,635
...tell them that we're coming...

1121
01:32:07,021 --> 01:32:08,182
...so that...

1122
01:32:08,398 --> 01:32:12,483
...they could start searching
for us in case we didn't make it.

1123
01:32:16,280 --> 01:32:18,443
And if Jack won't come with us...

1124
01:32:20,909 --> 01:32:24,618
...I'll just have to tell him that
we're going by ourselves.

1125
01:32:24,831 --> 01:32:26,787
That's all there is to it.

1126
01:32:28,167 --> 01:32:29,658
DANNY [IN TONY'S VOICE]:
<i>Redrum.</i>

1127
01:32:30,627 --> 01:32:32,288
<i>Redrum.</i>

1128
01:32:32,463 --> 01:32:35,797
<i>Redrum. Redrum.</i>

1129
01:32:36,801 --> 01:32:38,256
-Danny?
<i>-Redrum.</i>

1130
01:32:38,636 --> 01:32:42,378
<i>Redrum. Redrum.</i>

1131
01:32:42,556 --> 01:32:44,719
<i>-Redrum.</i>
-What's the matter, hon?

1132
01:32:44,893 --> 01:32:45,882
<i>Redrum!</i>

1133
01:32:46,060 --> 01:32:48,097
Are you having a bad dream?

1134
01:32:49,814 --> 01:32:51,600
Danny?

1135
01:32:54,027 --> 01:32:55,266
Hon?

1136
01:33:01,076 --> 01:33:04,989
<i>Danny's not here, Mrs. Torrance.</i>

1137
01:33:10,001 --> 01:33:11,490
Come on, hon.

1138
01:33:12,503 --> 01:33:13,914
Wake up.

1139
01:33:14,838 --> 01:33:17,126
You just had a bad dream.

1140
01:33:18,510 --> 01:33:20,671
Everything's okay.

1141
01:33:24,724 --> 01:33:28,591
<i>Danny can't wake up, Mrs. Torrance.</i>

1142
01:33:35,609 --> 01:33:36,600
Danny.

1143
01:33:38,070 --> 01:33:39,856
Wake up!

1144
01:33:41,032 --> 01:33:42,363
Come on.

1145
01:33:42,574 --> 01:33:44,110
Right now.

1146
01:33:44,577 --> 01:33:45,942
Wake up!

1147
01:33:49,998 --> 01:33:54,037
<i>Danny's gone away, Mrs. Torrance.</i>

1148
01:33:56,881 --> 01:33:57,871
Danny.

1149
